the poet, had a dream that lead

00:17:08.250 --> 00:17:12.716
to his poem, Kubla Khan and as you
know Keloy [assumed spelling] had

00:17:12.970 --> 00:17:16.636
the dream about the Benzene
ring; and I was wondering...

00:17:17.610 --> 00:17:17.650
&gt;&gt; Dr. Varmus: That's the
snake devouring its own tail.

00:17:21.170 --> 00:17:21.836
&gt;&gt; Audience question:
And I was wondering

00:17:23.170 --> 00:17:24.970
about the creative process.

00:17:25.170 --> 00:17:26.273
Is there such a thing that has
inspiration in science and if

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:30.800
so is it analogist to
that and what are...?

00:17:33.340 --> 00:17:34.750
&gt;&gt; Dr. Varmus: Yes and so I'm not
an authority on the creative process

00:17:36.530 --> 00:17:37.500
but one of the things I
try to do in this book is

00:17:38.760 --> 00:17:40.826
to relate how ideas came to me.

00:17:41.220 --> 00:17:45.353
I don't really understand how it
happens but one important idea

00:17:45.770 --> 00:17:48.170
that happens to lie in the narrative

00:17:48.390 --> 00:17:48.690
of the work I did is somebody
trying to find cancer genes.

00:17:51.890 --> 00:17:56.156
Just popped into my head when I
was wheeling my six-month old son

00:17:56.380 --> 00:17:59.713
through a churchyard during
a sabbatical in London.

00:18:00.260 --> 00:18:00.856
And I would say the important
thing there is the word sabbatical.

00:18:03.930 --> 00:18:07.263
Many of my fellow scientists
don't take a year off;

00:18:07.370 --> 00:18:07.700
they just plunge ahead all the time.

00:18:09.440 --> 00:18:09.706
They're working, working, working,

00:18:11.440 --> 00:18:12.706
trying to get their next
graph [assumed spelling],

00:18:13.440 --> 00:18:14.636
publish the next paper and I
think some time to get away

00:18:15.910 --> 00:18:18.443
from routine work and
think more deeply

00:18:20.260 --> 00:18:20.620
about science is an important thing.

00:18:22.300 --> 00:18:23.193
I'm in the midst of trying
to do an analogist thing

00:18:24.740 --> 00:18:26.406
at the NIH at the moment.

00:18:27.540 --> 00:18:30.940
We're in a phase of
remarkably dense data generation

00:18:33.210 --> 00:18:34.140
in the cancer research world; and
I've asked a number of my colleagues

00:18:36.880 --> 00:18:37.466
to come together and think not
about the next piece of data

00:18:40.160 --> 00:18:43.360
or how we interpret it
but what are the big ideas

00:18:43.500 --> 00:18:47.900
that we have not been working on
that we now could possibly answer.

00:18:49.360 --> 00:18:51.893
Hopefully out of that
process of saying

00:18:52.280 --> 00:18:52.693
to my colleagues I know
there are a lot of ideas

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:55.733
that we really haven't
thought much about.

00:18:57.000 --> 00:18:57.016
For example, we all say isn't
it amazing Lance Armstrong was--

00:19:01.050 --> 00:19:01.083
took chemotherapy for
testicular cancer

00:19:03.550 --> 00:19:03.773
and then won seven tours of France.

00:19:05.660 --> 00:19:05.930
But we don't think
much on a daily basis

00:19:07.990 --> 00:19:11.590
about why cyst platen actually
cures testicular cancer,

00:19:12.410 --> 00:19:14.810
and I find myself saying
all the time

00:19:14.900 --> 00:19:18.500
if we could make cancer a
controllable chronic disease,

00:19:18.810 --> 00:19:22.076
that would be a real step
forward and it would be.

00:19:23.320 --> 00:19:24.520
But I don't think we
should lose site of the fact

00:19:25.320 --> 00:19:26.020
that in some situations and there
are a few other diseases as well,

00:19:29.020 --> 00:19:31.020
chemotherapy does cure cancer.

00:19:31.020 --> 00:19:32.420
Why does that happen?

00:19:33.020 --> 00:19:34.686
It's a tough problem to answer
but I think we have tools

00:19:35.020 --> 00:19:36.820
to try to look at that now.

00:19:37.150 --> 00:19:39.816
Sorry. Over here; I'm
going to alternate.

00:19:40.120 --> 00:19:42.116
&gt;&gt; Audience question: My question
is about stem cell research.

00:19:42.190 --> 00:19:45.856
And given that it's an ethical
controversy isn't it true

00:19:46.260 --> 00:19:48.793
that we can make any
cell pluripotent--

00:19:48.960 --> 00:19:51.426
we have enough information
to do that.

00:19:51.940 --> 00:19:54.273
Can we now go about it another way?

00:19:55.060 --> 00:19:59.393
Why not, if not, is it not a form
of slavery if you can own a life

00:20:02.430 --> 00:20:03.006
like that and do whatever
you want with it otherwise?

00:20:05.320 --> 00:20:06.586
&gt;&gt; Dr. Varmus: Let me try
to answer that question.

00:20:07.320 --> 00:20:08.120
You're referring of
course to the induction

00:20:09.320 --> 00:20:10.120
of what are called
pluripotent stem cells--

00:20:11.320 --> 00:20:15.453
a very important method that may
actually be the most important

00:20:16.370 --> 00:20:19.170
technology in developing
therapeutic cells.

00:20:20.550 --> 00:20:22.323
But I would caution you a little bit
about that because we've only known

00:20:23.510 --> 00:20:26.976
about induced pluripotent
stem cells for a few years.

00:20:27.710 --> 00:20:32.176
We know already that they are not
identical to embryonic stem cells.

00:20:32.920 --> 00:20:36.386
There are limitations in
their potential very likely,

00:20:36.660 --> 00:20:37.056
they retain memory of the
kind of mature cell they were;

00:20:39.930 --> 00:20:44.463
it probably weighs around that but
if you want to compare those cells

00:20:47.540 --> 00:20:50.406
with the most well
understood primitive cell

00:20:50.930 --> 00:20:51.796
with maximum potential I think it is
important to carry out comparisons

00:20:54.730 --> 00:20:56.863
with human embryonic stem cells.

00:20:56.960 --> 00:21:01.293
Now, I think your other point about
enslaving a life depends a lot

00:21:02.360 --> 00:21:07.026
on what one considers life; and here
we have an area of moral argument.

00:21:07.600 --> 00:21:12.000
But I would point out what most
scientists are saying at this point

00:21:13.490 --> 00:21:17.690
about the process by which stem
cell research is being funded is

00:21:18.730 --> 00:21:21.730
that what they're asking
is that cells derived

00:21:23.600 --> 00:21:27.000
with non-federal money be
used or be able to be used

00:21:28.080 --> 00:21:30.746
with federal money to
do further studies.

00:21:31.290 --> 00:21:35.156
So there is a division that
was made traditionally accepted

00:21:35.220 --> 00:21:39.420
by the Bush Administration and
by the Clinton Administration too

00:21:40.440 --> 00:21:44.440
but also the Obama Administration
to allow work on stem cells

00:21:45.220 --> 00:21:49.420
that have been derived with
non-public money; non-federal money.

00:21:49.980 --> 00:21:51.846
That's an arguable position.

00:21:51.980 --> 00:21:53.100
I know there are people who feel
strongly the other way but I think

00:21:55.260 --> 00:21:55.656
that the benefits to human life of
working with cells that were derived

00:21:59.530 --> 00:22:04.063
from smaller cluster of cells that
were going to be discarded anyway,

00:22:06.020 --> 00:22:07.820
makes a lot of sense to me.

00:22:08.020 --> 00:22:09.020
[ Applause ]

00:22:10.020 --> 00:22:14.153
&gt;&gt; Audience question: Would you
say a few words about copyright

00:22:19.330 --> 00:22:19.683
and the way you can
do things over the web

00:22:21.710 --> 00:22:21.713
and perhaps even micro
dollar exchanges

00:22:24.240 --> 00:22:26.106
or something of that nature?

00:22:26.240 --> 00:22:27.240
&gt;&gt; Dr. Varmus: Sure I
assume you mean the context

00:22:28.440 --> 00:22:30.173
of scientific publication.

00:22:30.440 --> 00:22:31.040
Now I'm not anti-copyright
by any means.

00:22:32.440 --> 00:22:34.706
I believe the copyright is useful,

00:22:34.870 --> 00:22:35.220
but traditionally what
authors have done

00:22:37.120 --> 00:22:37.550
because there really
was no alternative,

00:22:39.290 --> 00:22:41.890
was to turn over copyright
to publishers

00:22:42.280 --> 00:22:42.846
after their papers were
accepted and allow publishers

00:22:45.180 --> 00:22:47.580
to do whatever they
like with papers.

00:22:47.820 --> 00:22:48.850
I think there's another way
to do things and that is

00:22:50.190 --> 00:22:53.123
to allow the copyright
to be held by authors.

00:22:53.780 --> 00:22:56.180
We're in, of course
a realm this day,

00:22:57.740 --> 00:22:58.556
of authors who make their living by
selling their work and I don't want

00:23:01.590 --> 00:23:01.720
to stop doing that; that's
very, very, important.

00:23:04.660 --> 00:23:06.860
But most of us who are scientists

00:23:07.460 --> 00:23:07.800
when we write scientific articles
we're not interested in money;

00:23:11.320 --> 00:23:12.986
we're interested in fame.

00:23:13.320 --> 00:23:14.520
We don't get money for
the publications we write.

00:23:15.320 --> 00:23:16.866
What we want to do we want
everybody to read our papers,

00:23:17.440 --> 00:23:17.610
we want those papers to be not just
famous by read by others and built

00:23:21.870 --> 00:23:21.876
on because the scientific process
depends on the dissemination

00:23:25.930 --> 00:23:30.330
of one's work and the greatest
possible access by other scientists.

00:23:30.870 --> 00:23:34.603
So in the world of open access
publication what's done is

00:23:35.450 --> 00:23:39.183
to allow the author to hold
the copyright and not turn it

00:23:39.330 --> 00:23:42.930
over to the Journal, and
grant a license to the Journal

00:23:43.190 --> 00:23:47.856
to publish the work, allow it to be
used freely for any purpose as long

00:23:49.040 --> 00:23:51.906
as acknowledgment of
authorship is retained.

00:23:52.960 --> 00:23:53.693
I think that's a very
reasonable position;

00:23:54.960 --> 00:23:55.960
it's one that's been
espoused by many journals

00:23:56.960 --> 00:24:00.626
and in the larger world it's
become routine now at least

00:24:01.500 --> 00:24:03.433
in the biomedical world, even

00:24:04.150 --> 00:24:08.150
if one doesn't publish an open
access journal but in journals

00:24:08.280 --> 00:24:11.413
that are either for-profit
or for the sustenance

00:24:11.890 --> 00:24:15.490
of scientific societies to
allow that work to be placed

00:24:16.660 --> 00:24:20.660
in a public repository called
Pub Med Central how to the NIH;

00:24:20.690 --> 00:24:22.086
and that has served the scientific
community exceedingly well.

00:24:23.360 --> 00:24:23.363
I believe the delay
of a year is excessive

00:24:26.090 --> 00:24:29.356
but the copyright rules
there have been worked out

00:24:30.320 --> 00:24:33.120
and we've made a big
improvement in the way

00:24:33.920 --> 00:24:36.853
in which we all access
scientific literature.

00:24:39.550 --> 00:24:43.283
Libraries have become smaller,
of course there's a crisis

00:24:45.160 --> 00:24:48.826
in university libraries
created by the pricing practices

00:24:49.720 --> 00:24:54.386
of many for-profit journals; and one
of the few ways to try to overcome

00:24:55.230 --> 00:24:55.866
that is by publishing by a
different business method,

00:24:58.060 --> 00:25:00.860
the open access method
which we know works.

00:25:01.420 --> 00:25:05.486
The open access publishing house
that I founded some years ago

00:25:05.560 --> 00:25:10.293
with my colleagues called the Public
Library of Science, now actually is

00:25:10.560 --> 00:25:14.493
in the black and doing experiments
with the excessive income

00:25:15.640 --> 00:25:16.266
that it receives from the
publication fee paid by the authors;

00:25:19.080 --> 00:25:19.146
and everything that's published

00:25:21.080 --> 00:25:21.813
by the group is made instantly
available to the entire world

00:25:24.280 --> 00:25:26.680
for free at the time of publication.

00:25:27.360 --> 00:25:28.360
Over here?

00:25:29.360 --> 00:25:31.370
&gt;&gt; Audience question: Because of my
personal and family history I feel

00:25:31.950 --> 00:25:36.283
that going to the doctor is very
important, having the colonoscopy

00:25:37.660 --> 00:25:42.393
and in my case being tested for skin
problems because I've had melanoma.

00:25:43.150 --> 00:25:47.550
Harold, how much is detection in
education for preventive medicine?

00:25:49.430 --> 00:25:51.630
How important is that for the NIH

00:25:51.970 --> 00:25:52.266
and what is your priority
with that-- with NIH?

00:25:54.740 --> 00:25:56.406
&gt;&gt; Dr. Varmus: Well, I think
this is extremely important

00:25:56.740 --> 00:26:00.406
and indeed we know that
prevention is often not as sexy.

00:26:00.530 --> 00:26:01.013
I'm not often asked when are
you going to prevent cancer;

00:26:03.780 --> 00:26:04.376
I'm asked when are you
going to cure cancer?

00:26:06.050 --> 00:26:06.503
Because there are no grateful
people who's cancers were prevented.

00:26:09.930 --> 00:26:14.330
So screening is incredibly important
and we need to do a better job

00:26:14.930 --> 00:26:15.603
but that's not just the job of the
NIH of course, but it's the job

00:26:18.590 --> 00:26:19.193
of personal physicians,
it's the job of the CDC,

00:26:21.120 --> 00:26:23.786
it's the job of the
Department and Health

00:26:24.170 --> 00:26:24.796
and Human Services more generally;
I'd like to think it's the job

00:26:27.810 --> 00:26:29.060
of the insurance companies which
have a great deal to benefit

00:26:30.560 --> 00:26:33.426
from preventing disease
becomes very costly.

00:26:33.540 --> 00:26:37.606
So this is a major thrust in my
own administration at the NCI.

00:26:37.780 --> 00:26:41.380
I think we can do a lot in
prevention both here at home

00:26:42.120 --> 00:26:43.853
and also around the world.

00:26:44.120 --> 00:26:47.920
We tend to neglect cancer as
a threat to poor populations;

00:26:48.730 --> 00:26:52.730
but the fact is that cancer is
a major burden of disease even

00:26:53.310 --> 00:26:55.253
in the poorest countries, and there
are many things that could be done--

00:26:56.100 --> 00:26:56.636
whether it's vaccination
against Hepatitis B

00:26:58.430 --> 00:27:02.430
or Papillomavirus infection, or
whether it's reduction in use

00:27:02.700 --> 00:27:06.966
of tobacco or early detection of
other cancers, simple surgeries,

00:27:08.050 --> 00:27:11.650
use of those anti-cancer
drugs who have gone off patent

00:27:13.330 --> 00:27:13.540
and become feasible for
use in poor countries.

00:27:16.120 --> 00:27:16.746
So from my point of view emphasizing
prevention and dissemination

00:27:19.760 --> 00:27:20.696
of what can be done, using
the Internet to help us

00:27:22.090 --> 00:27:22.213
out in dissemination is
a very important feature

00:27:25.100 --> 00:27:25.740
of what we see happening in
the next five to ten years.

00:27:28.060 --> 00:27:29.060
Over here?

00:27:30.540 --> 00:27:31.373
&gt;&gt; Audience question: Okay I guess
my question is I worked in the lab

00:27:34.240 --> 00:27:34.516
for a while so I understand
that there is some good science

00:27:37.830 --> 00:27:39.830
and some bad science and so...

00:27:39.830 --> 00:27:40.756
&gt;&gt; Dr. Varmus: What do
you mean by bad science?

00:27:41.970 --> 00:27:44.096
&gt;&gt; Audience question: Some science
that doesn't follow protocol perhaps

00:27:44.510 --> 00:27:48.843
as closely as others do; and so
the results may be somewhat skewed

00:27:48.960 --> 00:27:53.293
and so I see the benefit in having
peer review before publication.

00:27:54.040 --> 00:27:54.173
&gt;&gt; Dr. Varmus: Nothing I've said

00:27:56.040 --> 00:27:58.373
about open access publication has
anything to do with peer review.

00:27:58.040 --> 00:27:58.840
Open access publication
is all peer review.

00:28:00.040 --> 00:28:02.040
&gt;&gt; Audience question: Oh okay.

00:28:02.040 --> 00:28:03.840
But I think that the change

00:28:04.040 --> 00:28:04.790
in funding structure during
the Reagan era had some effect

00:28:07.090 --> 00:28:11.756
on willingness to share data, and I
wondered if there had been any sort

00:28:12.570 --> 00:28:15.370
of study that has looked
at how that change

00:28:17.280 --> 00:28:19.813
in funding structure
has had an effect.

00:28:19.940 --> 00:28:21.073
&gt;&gt; Dr. Varmus: Actually
I'm not sure what change

00:28:21.940 --> 00:28:23.673
in funding structure you're
talking about but I would say

00:28:23.940 --> 00:28:24.306
that on the whole the
willingness of scientists

00:28:26.640 --> 00:28:26.990
to share data has increased
enormously; and it's increased

00:28:30.090 --> 00:28:30.766
in part because of the
kind of science we're doing

00:28:32.680 --> 00:28:33.053
which is much more data intensive,
it requires teams much more often;

00:28:36.840 --> 00:28:39.773
a phenomena which I
think has its own dangers

00:28:39.850 --> 00:28:43.450
because sometimes the greatest
moments in science occur

00:28:43.560 --> 00:28:44.006
when a lone scientists is
thinking alone about a problem

00:28:46.780 --> 00:28:48.513
and not working in a team;

00:28:48.780 --> 00:28:49.980
but nevertheless there is
much more team science,

00:28:50.780 --> 00:28:50.786
much more interaction
among scientists

00:28:53.240 --> 00:28:55.906
of different institutions,
and the nature

00:28:56.070 --> 00:28:56.130
of the science itself
demands more sharing.

00:28:58.810 --> 00:29:02.876
In addition to that voluntary
willingness to do more as teams,

00:29:03.410 --> 00:29:08.076
the NCI and other institutes of the
NIH demand sharing policies as part

00:29:08.710 --> 00:29:11.576
of grant applications
and I think that we're

00:29:12.530 --> 00:29:12.930
on a good trajectory in that regard.

00:29:14.530 --> 00:29:14.676
&gt;&gt; Audience question:
Can you talk a little bit

00:29:17.450 --> 00:29:19.316
about the funding decisions.

00:29:19.450 --> 00:29:23.516
How it's decided which programs
get funded and related to that

00:29:24.170 --> 00:29:26.503
about publicizing what the NIH does

00:29:26.970 --> 00:29:27.580
so you can build support
within the community.

00:29:29.360 --> 00:29:29.936
&gt;&gt; Dr. Varmus: Right well
on your latter topic,

00:29:31.850 --> 00:29:36.516
I think we have pretty good support
from the American community for NIH

00:29:37.570 --> 00:29:37.916
and what it does, but it
could be a lot more informed

00:29:40.690 --> 00:29:43.490
and we are responsible
for creating stories

00:29:43.830 --> 00:29:44.040
that reflect what we're doing,
explain to the public more fully.

00:29:47.820 --> 00:29:48.090
And I think the instinct
is to support the NIH

00:29:50.550 --> 00:29:54.016
because life expectancy in
this country has improved,

00:29:54.520 --> 00:29:54.586
we're the pioneers in the world

00:29:56.520 --> 00:29:57.020
and generating sophisticated
new approaches to healthcare.

00:29:59.820 --> 00:30:01.553
And I think the reputation

00:30:01.820 --> 00:30:02.753
of the NIH is strong
but I do agree with you.

00:30:03.820 --> 00:30:04.883
In fact I was meeting with
some journalists today to talk

00:30:06.490 --> 00:30:09.756
about how the NCI should
sort of redraft its story

00:30:10.390 --> 00:30:10.920
so we're not worried day by day
about whether we're winning the war

00:30:14.260 --> 00:30:14.870
in cancer, but instead talking
about what has actually happened,

00:30:17.850 --> 00:30:22.050
how our understanding of why a
normal cell becomes a cancer cell

00:30:22.380 --> 00:30:22.853
can be translated into
new ways to prevent

00:30:24.640 --> 00:30:26.640
and treat and diagnose cancer.

00:30:26.640 --> 00:30:28.573
So I agree with those points.

00:30:28.640 --> 00:30:30.040
Your first point was?

00:30:30.640 --> 00:30:31.906
&gt;&gt; Audience question: About
the funding decision--

00:30:32.640 --> 00:30:33.440
how do you decide what
programs get funded?

00:30:34.640 --> 00:30:35.800
&gt;&gt; Dr. Varmus: First of all
there's a macro set of decisions.

00:30:37.480 --> 00:30:37.733
How much does the President ask
Congress to give to the NIH?

00:30:41.160 --> 00:30:41.973
How does Congress decide how much
it's going to give to the NIH

00:30:44.480 --> 00:30:47.080
and those are issues
that we participate

00:30:48.170 --> 00:30:49.970
in by telling the President

00:30:50.490 --> 00:30:50.880
and Congress what we
could do with more money?

00:30:53.100 --> 00:30:56.633
In general, Congress and the
Presidents have been kind

00:30:57.330 --> 00:30:57.530
to the NIH; we're probably
among the agencies least likely

00:31:00.930 --> 00:31:04.196
to have our budget cut at
a time of verconian cuts

00:31:04.210 --> 00:31:06.676
that are talked about
by both parties.

00:31:07.200 --> 00:31:09.800
And but you're asking
about is how do we

00:31:11.600 --> 00:31:12.693
at the Cancer Institute
decide which programs to fund.

00:31:14.040 --> 00:31:14.240
And that's a complicated process.

00:31:16.040 --> 00:31:17.453
Some of its determined simply
by peer review we're saying

00:31:18.360 --> 00:31:18.693
that grants better than that grant.

00:31:20.360 --> 00:31:22.333
Some of its decided by saying you
know we looked at our portfolio,

00:31:22.720 --> 00:31:27.120
we're not doing anything on cancer
X and there's a new opportunity.

00:31:27.720 --> 00:31:30.920
So you've got to weigh
